## Setup Instructions

### 1. GitHub Repository Setup

#### Create Repository
```bash
# Create new repository on GitHub named "CloudDevOpsProject"
# Then clone it locally
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME/CloudDevOpsProject.git
cd CloudDevOpsProject
```

#### Initialize Project
```bash
# Copy all project files to the repository
# Add and commit
git add .
git commit -m "Initial project setup with complete structure"
git push origin main
```

---

### 2. Docker Containerization

#### Build Docker Image Locally
```bash
# Navigate to project root
cd CloudDevOpsProject

# Build the Docker image
docker build -t ivolve-app:latest .

# Test the image locally
docker run -p 5000:5000 ivolve-app:latest

# Access application at http://localhost:5000
```

#### Push to DockerHub
```bash
# Login to DockerHub
docker login -u YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME

# Tag the image
docker tag ivolve-app:latest YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/ivolve:latest

# Push to DockerHub
docker push YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/ivolve:latest
```

**Dockerfile Explanation:**
- Base image: `python:3.11-slim` (lightweight)
- Working directory: `/app`
- Installs Flask dependencies
- Exposes port 5000
- Runs Flask application

---

### 3. Kubernetes Setup

#### Option A: Using Minikube (Local Development)

```bash
# Start Minikube
minikube start --driver=docker

# Create iVolve namespace
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/namespace.yaml

# Deploy application
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/service.yaml

# Check deployment status
kubectl get pods -n ivolve
kubectl get svc -n ivolve

# Access application (Minikube)
minikube service ivolve-svc -n ivolve
```

#### Option B: Using EKS (AWS)

```bash
# Configure AWS CLI
aws configure

# Create EKS cluster (using eksctl or Terraform)
eksctl create cluster --name ivolve-cluster --region us-east-1

# Update kubeconfig
aws eks update-kubeconfig --name ivolve-cluster --region us-east-1

# Apply Kubernetes manifests
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/namespace.yaml
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f kubernetes/service.yaml

# Get LoadBalancer URL
kubectl get svc -n ivolve
```

**Important:** Update `YOUR_DOCKERHUB_USERNAME/ivolve:latest` in `kubernetes/deployment.yaml` with your actual DockerHub image.

